The '''Genomics Institute of the Novartis Research Foundation''' (GNF) is a research institution specializing in basic biological as well as [[drug discovery]] research using [[High-throughput screening|high-throughput]] techniques. The institute was originally known as the Novartis Institute for Functional Genomics and this name is still used sometimes.<ref>[http://www.prnewswire.com/cgi-bin/stories.pl?ACCT=104&STORY=/www/story/10-28-1998/0000787716&EDATE= PR Newswire - news distribution, targeting and monitoring]</ref><ref>[http://www.molsoft.com/molgnfpressrapril12.html Molsoft L.L.C.]</ref> It is a {{convert|60000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} research center<ref name="GNF.org">[http://www.gnf.org/about/ GNF.org]</ref> located in the [[Torrey Pines, San Diego, California|Torrey Pines]] Science Park in [[La Jolla, California]], and was started in 1999. The institute was originally funded through the [[Novartis Foundation]] while the foundation was in existence, and is currently funded directly by [[Novartis]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Together with the [[Novartis Institute for Tropical Diseases]] (NITD) in Singapore and [[Friedrich Miescher]] Institute (FMI) in [[Basel]], GNF comprises the corporate research arm of [[Novartis]].<ref>[http://www.novartis.com/research/corporate-research/gnf.shtml Novartis]</ref> The institute has more than 500 employees.<ref>[http://schultz.scripps.edu/ The Scripps Research Institute - Creating Hope through Science]</ref> The institute was founded by [[Peter G. Schultz|Peter Schultz]], was also the director for several years. From 2014 the institute is led by [[Gerald Joyce]].
